---

<PageLayout
  title="Dersimelagon (MT-7117): the oral MC1R agonist chasing the afamelanotide target"
  kicker="Investigational"
  description="Dersimelagon is an investigational once-daily pill that activates MC1R — the small-molecule, oral answer to afamelanotide's implant. Its Phase 3 trial in erythropoietic protoporphyria read out positive in 2026, and it has a second life in fibrosis."
  updated="2026"
  about={[
    { name: 'Dersimelagon', type: 'Drug', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dersimelagon'] },
    { name: 'Melanocortin 1 receptor', type: 'MedicalEntity', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanocortin_1_receptor'] },
    { name: 'Erythropoietic protoporphyria', type: 'MedicalCondition', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erythropoietic_protoporphyria'] },
  ]}
>
  <KeyTakeaways
    items={[
      'Dersimelagon (MT-7117) is an investigational oral, selective MC1R agonist — a small-molecule tablet, not a peptide.',
      'It targets the same receptor and strategy as afamelanotide (build protective pigment), but as a once-daily pill rather than a two-monthly implant.',
      'Its global Phase 3 INSPIRE trial in erythropoietic protoporphyria (EPP) and X-linked protoporphyria (XLP) reported positive topline results in January 2026.',
      'It has a distinct second use: preclinical work shows MC1R activation may be disease-modifying in systemic sclerosis, a fibrotic disease.',
      'Its main side effects are mechanism-based pigment changes — skin hyperpigmentation and freckle-like lentigines.',
    ]}
  />

  <p>
    Dersimelagon — development code <strong>MT-7117</strong> — is what happens when you
    take the <a href="/afamelanotide">afamelanotide</a> idea and try to put it in a pill.
    It aims at the same target, <a href="/receptors/mc1r">MC1R</a>, with the same
    strategy — build protective pigment to defend against light — but as an oral
    small-molecule drug rather than an injected peptide implant.<Cite n={1} />
  </p>

  <h2>Same target, different form</h2>
  <p>
    Afamelanotide proved that switching on MC1R can treat the light-sensitivity disease
    <a href="/afamelanotide">erythropoietic protoporphyria</a>, but it does so as a
    two-monthly implant placed by a clinician. Dersimelagon is the attempt to deliver the
    same benefit more conveniently: a <strong>once-daily tablet</strong> a patient can take
    at home.<Cite n={1} /> Because it is a small molecule rather than an α-MSH-like peptide,
    it can be absorbed orally — a meaningful practical difference for a chronic,
    preventive therapy.
  </p>

  <h2>The Phase 3 result</h2>
  <p>
    Dersimelagon's lead program is in EPP and the related disorder
    <strong>X-linked protoporphyria (XLP)</strong>. In <strong>January 2026</strong>,
    Tanabe Pharma America reported positive topline efficacy and safety results from the
    global Phase 3 <strong>INSPIRE</strong> trial in adult and adolescent patients — the
    key clinical milestone on its path toward becoming an oral option alongside the
    approved implant.<Cite n={3} /> As with every drug in this family, the trial's most
    common side effects were mechanism-based pigment changes: skin hyperpigmentation and
    freckle-like lentigines, the expected signature of MC1R activation.<Cite n={1} />
  </p>

  <h2>A second life in fibrosis</h2>
  <p>
    Dersimelagon's more surprising story is outside pigment biology altogether. Preclinical
    research shows that MC1R activation can produce <strong>disease-modifying,
    anti-fibrotic effects</strong> in models of <strong>systemic sclerosis</strong> — a
    serious autoimmune disease in which skin and internal organs become scarred and
    stiff.<Cite n={2} /> In those models, dersimelagon suppressed skin fibrosis and lung
    inflammation, pointing to a role for the melanocortin system in tissue scarring that
    has nothing to do with sunlight. It is an early but striking example of the same
    receptor being repurposed for a completely different disease.
  </p>

  <h2>The honest bottom line</h2>
  <p>
    Dersimelagon is investigational — promising Phase 3 data is not the same as approval,
    and the fibrosis work is still preclinical. But it captures two live themes on the
    melanocortin frontier: making these drugs easier to take (a pill instead of an
    implant), and pushing MC1R beyond pigment into inflammation and fibrosis. For the
    approved drug it is chasing, see <a href="/afamelanotide">afamelanotide</a>; for where
    it sits among everything else in development, see the
    <a href="/pipeline">melanocortin pipeline</a>.
  </p>

  <div class="not-prose mt-8 rounded-lg border border-[var(--border)] bg-[var(--accent-soft)] p-6 text-sm leading-relaxed">
    <p class="font-medium text-[var(--text)]">Education, not a protocol</p>
    <p class="mt-2 text-[var(--text)]">
      This page explains an investigational drug and its trial status. It does not provide
      dosing or usage instructions and is not medical advice. Dersimelagon is not FDA-approved;
      its safety and efficacy are still being established. See the
      <a href="/about">editorial standards</a>.
    </p>
  </div>

  <FAQ items={faqs} />

  <References items={references} />

  <RelatedPages slug="dersimelagon" />
</PageLayout>
